  "texts": [
    "See generallyCoglianese & Lehr, supra note 16 (discussing the role of systemic transparency in legitimizing algorithmic governance).",
    "See Post, supra note 19, at 48 (\"AI learns as it receives feedback about its decisions.",
    "Because AI algorithms learn through iterative training, politically appropriate participation in this training might offer the possibility of legitimating the decisions of AI.",
    "See, e.g., Jon Elster, Legislatures as Constituent Assemblies, in THE LEAST EXAMINED BRANCH: THE ROLE OF LEGISLATURES IN THE CONSTITUTIONAL STATE 181, 197 (Richard W. Bauman & Tsvi Kahana eds., 2006) (\"[T]hese public processes can take place at the upstream stage and perhaps also at the downstream stage, but.",
    "between these two stages the writing of the constitution should be shielded from the public."
  ]
}